  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":392,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently — first 5 minutes should feel almost embarrassingly easy. Let your body wake up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. This is aerobic base building — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 5 minutes. Finish feeling like you had more in the tank.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of easy walking or very slow jogging before you find your rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Slow to a walk for 2-3 minutes at the end. Add dynamic stretching — leg swings, hip circles — if time allows.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the aerobic foundation for the week. At your current fitness, roughly 80% of your weekly volume should feel like this — genuinely comfortable. Your easy pace range is 5:52–6:43/km, and anywhere in that window is correct. If you feel flat from the weekend's long run, stay closer to 6:43. This isn't a junk mile day — easy running builds mitochondrial density and improves fat oxidation, both critical for half marathon performance.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":293,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Full 15-minute easy warmup — this is non-negotiable before threshold work. Include 4-6 strides in the final 2 minutes to prime your legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":293,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Threshold pace is 4:53/km — comfortably hard. You should be able to say a few words but not hold a conversation. This is the pace that raises your lactate threshold, which is the #1 physiological predictor of half marathon performance.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy to flush lactate and bring your heart rate back down gradually. Don't skip this — it aids recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final walk cooldown and light stretching, especially hip flexors and calves.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running followed by 4-6 strides (20-second accelerations with full recovery between each). This primes your neuromuscular system for the quality work ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 15 minutes easy running after the tempo block. Your legs should feel noticeably lighter by the end.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold work is the cornerstone of half marathon training. Your threshold pace of 4:53/km is the speed at which lactate production and clearance are roughly balanced — training at this effort pushes that balance point higher over time. The 20-minute continuous tempo is a solid introduction at this phase of your training. The effort should feel 'comfortably hard' — a 7 out of 10. If it feels like a 9, back off slightly. Given your IT band history, make sure your warmup is thorough and you're not landing with excessive crossover stride.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery or Rest Day\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":0,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional 20-30 minutes of very light cross-training (swimming, cycling, yoga) or complete rest. The goal is active recovery, not fitness building.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No running today. If doing cross-training, ease in gradually.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with gentle stretching — focus on IT band, hip flexors, and glutes to support your injury history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a deliberate recovery day after back-to-back running days. Adaptation happens during rest, not during the run itself. If you feel the urge to do more, remind yourself that your Tuesday tempo has already done the stimulus work — Wednesday is when your body actually responds to it. Optional light cross-training is fine if you're feeling restless, but keep the heart rate low and effort gentle.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":270,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy running. Include 4-6 strides in the final 2 minutes before intervals begin.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":270,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 3-minute intervals at 4:30/km (your interval pace). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — not an all-out sprint. Recovery between reps is 90 seconds of easy jogging.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"90 seconds to 2 minutes of very easy jogging between each interval. Recover enough to run the next rep at the same quality — if you can't, extend recovery slightly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy running to complete the session. This is important — don't just stop after the last interval.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Full 15-minute easy warmup with strides. VO2max work puts significant demand on your cardiovascular and muscular systems — a proper warmup reduces injury risk and improves interval quality.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running after the final interval. Add light stretching for IT band and hip area post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals at 4:30/km directly stress your aerobic ceiling — the maximum rate at which your body can use oxygen. Training at this intensity is one of the most potent stimuli for improving running economy and aerobic power. For a 1:45 half marathon, you'll need to sustain roughly 5:00/km, so these intervals at 4:30 build the capacity that makes race pace feel manageable. Five 3-minute reps is an appropriate volume for where you are right now. Pay close attention to your form in the final two reps — that's where IT band strain tends to creep in if you're fatiguing.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":403,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":403,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Genuinely easy — stay at the relaxed end of your easy range (6:30–6:43/km). This is a recovery run, not a training stimulus. If your legs feel heavy, slow down further or shorten to 30 minutes.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — just start very slowly and let the run itself serve as warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5-minute walk and gentle stretching. Focus on IT band stretch (standing or lying figure-4) and hip flexor lunge stretch.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run maintains aerobic frequency without adding meaningful fatigue before Saturday's rest and Sunday's long run. The key word is 'easy.' After Thursday's intervals, your legs may still be carrying some residual fatigue — that's normal and expected. Running gently through that fatigue, rather than resting completely, keeps blood flowing to the muscles and accelerates recovery. Keep your ego out of the pace on this one.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Rest or Optional Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional 20-30 minutes of yoga, swimming, or easy cycling. Emphasis on mobility and recovery rather than cardiovascular load. Foam rolling IT band and glutes is a great use of this time.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"If cross-training, ease in gently with 5 minutes of very light movement.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Prioritize hip and IT band mobility work. Consider a 10-15 minute stretching or foam rolling session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your buffer day before Sunday's long run — the most important workout of the week. Complete rest is ideal if you're feeling any fatigue accumulation. Light mobility work or a gentle swim is fine if you want to stay active. The goal is arriving at Sunday's long run with fresh legs and a ready mind. Given your IT band history, this is a great day for targeted glute and hip strengthening (clamshells, single-leg bridges) to support the connective tissue.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":15,\"target_duration_minutes\":97,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":392,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":392,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 7 minutes very relaxed — let your body ease into the effort. Don't look at pace, just feel comfortable.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":83,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":392,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady easy pace (5:52–6:30/km). The long run is about time on feet and aerobic adaptation, not speed. If you feel strong in the final 20 minutes, you may pick up slightly — but never chase pace at the expense of completing the distance.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":403,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 7 minutes. Finish feeling controlled and strong — not collapsed. Walk the final 2-3 minutes.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute walk before you begin running. The first mile should feel almost too easy — that's correct.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3-5 minutes after finishing. Rehydrate immediately. Spend 10-15 minutes on post-run stretching — calves, hamstrings, hip flexors, and IT band. This is especially important given your injury history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the single most important session of the week for half marathon preparation. At 15km this week, you're building on your current 14km long run with a modest, safe increase. The physiological benefits are significant: increased glycogen storage capacity, improved fat oxidation, enhanced mitochondrial density, and the connective tissue adaptation that lets you handle race distance. Your target of 1:45 for the half marathon means about 5:00/km race pace — your long runs should feel noticeably easier than that, which at 5:52–6:43/km they absolutely should. Keep the effort genuinely conversational throughout. Given your 75-minute max preference, this session at roughly 97 minutes slightly exceeds that — if that's a hard constraint, you could trim to 14km this week and build from there, but the long run is where the most important half marathon adaptations happen. Worth a conversation about flexibility on Sundays.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
